{"id": 223771582, "title": "About one Quebec child per day taken to ER for drowning, near-drowning: Study", "text": "He says the study, which he led along with Quebec\u2019s public health institute and coroner\u2019s office, looked at all children\u2019s drowning deaths, ER visits or hospital admissions between 2017 and 2021. The research found children between the age of one and four are most at risk, and drownings or near-drownings are more likely to occur on weekends or in pools without proper fencing. While Quebec law requires pool owners to install appropriate fencing, owners of older pools have until 2025 to comply. Wissanji says that for every fatal drowning, there are more than 10 children taken to the ER or hospitalized due to water accidents that can happen over just a few seconds.", "summary": "MONTREAL &#8212; New research has found an average of one child a day goes to the emergency room for a drowning or near-drowning in Quebec during the summer months. The study will be officially published later this year but Dr. Hussein Wissanji, a pediatric surgeon at the Montreal Children&#8217;s Hospital, says he&#8217;s publicizing the results [&#8230;]", "url": "https://torontosun.com/news/national/about-one-quebec-child-per-day-taken-to-er-for-drowning-near-drowning-study", "image": "https://smartcdn.gprod.postmedia.digital/torontosun/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/que-drowning-study-20240526.jpg?quality=100&strip=all", "video": "", "publish_date": "2024-05-26 17:03:39", "author": "Canadian Press", "authors": ["Canadian Press"], "language": "en", "source_country": "CA", "sentiment": 0.205}